 :
 :
 :
 :BRUTUS
 :
 :Come, poor remains of friends, rest on this rock.
 :[He sits down.]
 :
 :CLITUS
 :Statilius showed the torchlight, but, my lord,
S:He came not back. He is or ta'en or slain.
 :
 :
 :
S:BRUTUS
 :
 :Sit thee down, Clitus. Slaying is the word;
 :
 :It is a deed in fashion. Hark thee, Clitus.
 :
 :[He whispers to Clitus.]
 :
 :CLITUS
 :What, I, my lord? No, not for all the world.
 :
 :BRUTUS
S:
 :Peace, then, no words.
 :
S:
 :
 :CLITUS  I'll rather kill myself.
 :
 :
 :
 :BRUTUS
 :Hark thee, Dardanus.	[He whispers to Dardanus.]
S:
 :
 :DARDANUS  Shall I do such a deed?
 :
 :
 :
S:CLITUS  O Dardanus!
 :
 :
 :
 :DARDANUS  O Clitus!
 :
 :[Dardanus and Clitus step aside.]
 :
 :CLITUS
 :What ill request did Brutus make to thee?
 :
 :DARDANUS
S:
 :To kill him, Clitus. Look, he meditates.
 :
 :
 :
 :CLITUS
 :
S:Now is that noble vessel full of grief,
 :
 :That it runs over even at his eyes.
 :
 :
 :
S:BRUTUS
 :
 :Come hither, good Volumnius. List a word.
 :
 :
 :
 :VOLUMNIUS
 :What says my lord?
 :
 :BRUTUS  Why this, Volumnius:
S:The ghost of Caesar hath appeared to me
 :
 :Two several times by night--at Sardis once
 :
S:And this last night here in Philippi fields.
 :
 :I know my hour is come.
 :
 :
 :
 :VOLUMNIUS  Not so, my lord.
 :
 :BRUTUS
 :Nay, I am sure it is, Volumnius.
 :Thou seest the world, Volumnius, how it goes.
 :Our enemies have beat us to the pit.	[Low alarums.]
S:
 :It is more worthy to leap in ourselves
 :
 :Than tarry till they push us. Good Volumnius,
 :
 :Thou know'st that we two went to school together;
 :
S:Even for that our love of old, I prithee,
 :
